        depth: 1,
        title: "A Word as a Door",
        body: `<p>Imagine that everything you own — your bank account, your medical history, the photographs of your children, every email you have ever written — sits inside a single room, and the door to that room is held shut by a word. Not a key, not a fingerprint, not a guard. Just a word, of your own choosing, written down somewhere and remembered.</p><p>Most of us choose poorly. The most common password in the world, year after year, is "123456." The second is "password." The third is the name of the person typing it. We choose this way not because we are foolish but because we have too many doors. The average internet user has more than a hundred accounts, each demanding its own word, and human memory was not designed for this.</p><p>The result is a slow, quiet crisis. Every year, billions of credentials leak from breached databases — names, emails, hashed passwords, sometimes far more. Criminals collect them, sort them, cross-reference them, and try every combination against every other site. A single weak password reused across three sites becomes a master key. The door you thought was closed has been ajar for years.</p><p>Understanding how passwords actually work — and what to do instead — is one of the most consequential bits of literacy a person can pick up in an afternoon.</p>`,
