      {
        depth: 5,
        title: "Entropy by the Numbers, and a TOTP Walkthrough",
        body: `<p>The honest mathematics of password strength is straightforward enough to work out on paper. The formula for the entropy of a random password is:</p><p><code>H = log<sub>2</sub>(N<sup>L</sup>) = L · log<sub>2</sub>(N)</code></p><p>where N is the alphabet size and L is the length. For a 12-character password drawn from 95 printable ASCII characters (lowercase + uppercase + digits + symbols):</p><pre><code>N = 95
L = 12
H = 12 · log2(95)
  = 12 · 6.5699
  = 78.84 bits

Total possible passwords: 95^12 ≈ 5.4 × 10^23

At a generous offline cracking rate of 10^12 guesses per second
(roughly a high-end GPU cluster against bcrypt):

  time = 5.4 × 10^23 / 10^12  =  5.4 × 10^11 seconds
       ≈ 17,000 years (average: half of that, 8,500 years)</code></pre><p>Now consider the alternative: four random words from the EFF long wordlist (7,776 entries):</p><pre><code>N = 7,776 (the wordlist size)
L = 4 (number of words)
H = 4 · log2(7776)
  = 4 · 12.925
  = 51.7 bits

Six words gives 77.5 bits — comparable to a 12-character random ASCII password,
and dramatically easier to remember and type.</code></pre><p>The "correct horse battery staple" comic was making a specific claim about this trade-off. Four randomly chosen words have around 44 bits of entropy if drawn from a 2,000-word vocabulary; comfortably enough for most purposes, especially when slowed by a key derivation function. A 12-character random ASCII master password and a six-word random passphrase both put you well past the cliff where brute force stops mattering and the attacker has to look for other ways in.</p><p><strong>TOTP, end to end.</strong> Defined in RFC 6238, TOTP builds on the HOTP algorithm of RFC 4226. When you scan a QR code to enable 2FA, the site sends your authenticator app a shared secret K, typically 20 bytes (160 bits), base32-encoded. The algorithm runs as follows:</p><pre><code>1. T = floor( (current Unix time in seconds) / 30 )
     T is the time step — a counter that ticks once every 30 seconds.

2. HMAC = HMAC-SHA1( K, T as 8-byte big-endian integer )
     A 20-byte (160-bit) message authentication code.

3. offset = HMAC[19] AND 0x0F
     The low 4 bits of the last byte select a starting position within the HMAC.

4. truncated = ( (HMAC[offset]   AND 0x7F) &lt;&lt; 24 )
              | ( (HMAC[offset+1] AND 0xFF) &lt;&lt; 16 )
              | ( (HMAC[offset+2] AND 0xFF) &lt;&lt;  8 )
              | ( (HMAC[offset+3] AND 0xFF)       )
     Take 31 bits from a dynamically chosen position in the HMAC.

5. code = truncated MOD 1,000,000
     Reduce to a 6-digit number, zero-padded.

Display the code. Tick again in 30 seconds.</code></pre><p>Both the server and your phone hold the same secret K and the same clock. They independently compute the same code. There is no network communication between your phone and the server during code generation — which is why TOTP works on a plane with no signal. The risk surface is the shared secret: if a server is breached and the unencrypted secrets are exfiltrated, every account on that server can be impersonated until users re-enroll. This is why hardware keys and passkeys, which never share a secret with the server (the server holds only a public key), are structurally more secure than TOTP.</p><p><strong>Why "correct horse battery staple" works.</strong> The xkcd argument was not that the passphrase is unguessable in isolation. It was that the entropy of a random passphrase (44+ bits for four words from a large list) exceeds the entropy of a typical human-chosen "strong" password (around 25 bits, due to predictable substitution patterns), <em>while being far easier to remember</em>. The strength comes from the randomness of selection, not the cleverness of construction. The moment a human chooses the words themselves — picking memorable, semantically related words — most of the entropy collapses, and a passphrase cracker will find it in hours.</p><p>The current NIST guidance (SP 800-63B-3, updated 2024) reflects all of this. No forced periodic resets. No required character classes. Minimum length of 8 (15 recommended for accounts with elevated risk). Reject passwords that appear in known breach lists. Allow paste. Allow long passphrases. Encourage password managers. Encourage phishing-resistant MFA. It is the single best, plainest piece of authentication guidance any government has ever published.</p>`
      },
      {
        depth: 6,
        title: "Passkeys, Post-Password Futures, and Open Questions",
        body: `<p>The honest end of the password story is that passwords are slowly being replaced. The architecture that will replace them, after thirty years of incremental attempts, is <strong>WebAuthn</strong> — a W3C standard finalized in 2019, with FIDO2 as the broader umbrella encompassing the client-to-authenticator protocol (CTAP2). WebAuthn is implemented in every modern browser and supported by every major platform.</p><p>The mechanism is elegant. When you register with a site, your device generates a fresh public-private key pair specifically for that site. The site stores only your public key. To log in, the site sends a random challenge; your device signs it with the private key (after unlocking the key via biometric or PIN); the site verifies the signature with the public key. The private key never leaves your device. There is no shared secret to steal in a database breach. The signed challenge is bound to the site's origin, so a phishing site cannot trick your device into signing for the wrong domain.</p><p><strong>Passkeys</strong> are the consumer branding of WebAuthn credentials that are synchronized across a user's devices, typically via iCloud Keychain, Google Password Manager, or a third-party manager like 1Password or Bitwarden. Approved at the device by Touch ID, Face ID, Windows Hello, or a PIN. Apple, Google, and Microsoft committed to the platform jointly in May 2022 and have rolled out support steadily since. By 2025, most large consumer sites — Amazon, eBay, PayPal, GitHub, Google, Microsoft, Apple, Cloudflare, X, Reddit — support passkeys.</p><p>The transition is uneven. The standards are mature; the user experience is still rough; account recovery is the hardest unsolved problem. (If you lose all the devices that hold your passkey, what then? The current answer — sync via a cloud provider — re-introduces a kind of master password problem at a different layer.) Enterprise adoption faces additional friction: shared accounts, contractor onboarding, devices managed by IT, and the long tail of legacy systems that only speak passwords.</p><p>The deeper frontier is the post-quantum threat. The public-key cryptography underpinning WebAuthn (currently ECDSA over P-256 or Ed25519) would be broken by a sufficiently large quantum computer running Shor's algorithm. NIST finalized its first post-quantum signature standards in 2024 — CRYSTALS-Dilithium (now ML-DSA) and SPHINCS+ — and the FIDO Alliance has working groups planning the migration. The migration will take years.</p><p>The cultural frontier is the harder one. The seminal paper on password problems remains William Cheswick and Robert Morris's analysis of Unix passwords (1979) and the cracking work of Daniel Klein in 1990, which found that 25% of passwords could be guessed in a few hours of computation — a figure that has barely moved in three decades. The standard reference for usable security is Ross Anderson's <em>Security Engineering</em> (Wiley, third edition 2020). The most-cited modern analysis of credential-stuffing attacks is the Verizon Data Breach Investigations Report, published annually; the 2023 edition attributed 49% of all breaches to stolen credentials. NIST SP 800-63 is the operational standard most security teams build to. The OWASP Authentication Cheat Sheet is the most widely consulted practitioner reference.</p><p>The deeper question is whether passwords were ever a good idea. Roger Needham, who designed the Cambridge ring authentication system in the 1970s and helped invent the Kerberos protocol, observed that passwords are a security mechanism so flawed in concept that they survive only because everything proposed to replace them has been worse. The most credible candidate to finally replace them — passkeys — is, at the end of fifty years of effort, public-key cryptography invoked by a fingerprint. The wonder is that it took this long.</p>`
      }
