        body: `<p>You type a few words into a bar at the top of a window and press Enter. For a fraction of a second — less time than it takes to blink — nothing seems to happen. Then a world arrives. Headlines settle into place. Images bloom into focus. A column of text aligns itself, a button glows when your cursor crosses it, a menu slides open at your touch. It feels like opening a door onto a room that was always there, waiting.</p><p>But there was no room. What actually crossed the wire was a torrent of raw text — angle brackets and curly braces, a recipe written in three different languages, arriving in pieces and out of order. None of it was a page. It was instructions for building a page, and something on your machine had to read those instructions and build the thing, fast enough that you never noticed the construction.</p><p>That something is the browser, the most-used and least-understood program most of us run. It is a tireless interpreter, a chef handed a recipe and expected to plate the meal before the diner looks up. It does this hundreds of times an hour, billions of times a second across the planet, and almost always without complaint. This is the story of what happens in that blink.</p>`,
