        title: "Why Fast Feels Fast",
        body: `<p>Speed on the web is not one thing but a balance of costs, and the browser's whole art lies in paying the cheapest one it can. The three operations at the end of the rendering path are priced very differently. A <strong>reflow</strong> (layout) is expensive: change one element's width and the browser may have to recompute the geometry of much of the page, because boxes push on their neighbors like furniture in a crowded room. A <strong>repaint</strong> is cheaper: change only a color or a shadow, and geometry is untouched — the browser merely refills pixels. Cheapest of all is a pure <strong>composite</strong>: move or fade an existing layer, and the GPU slides it around without re-laying-out or repainting anything. This is why seasoned developers animate with <code>transform</code> and <code>opacity</code> rather than with <code>width</code> or <code>top</code> — they are choosing the cheap lane on purpose.</p><p>And there is, fundamentally, one lane. Most of this work happens on a single thread: the <strong>main thread</strong>, which JavaScript, style calculation, layout, and paint all share. They take turns. The browser orchestrates those turns with the <strong>event loop</strong> — a simple, relentless cycle: run a task to completion, then handle pending events, then render a frame if it's time, then repeat. Because tasks run to completion, a single <em>long task</em> — a function that chews on a big array for 200 milliseconds — blocks everything behind it. Clicks go unheard, animations freeze, the page feels stuck. The screen wants a fresh frame roughly every 16 milliseconds (60 frames per second); blow that budget and the user feels the jank in their bones, even if they cannot name it.</p><p>To hide the latency it cannot eliminate, the browser cheats — productively. While a blocking script runs, a separate <strong>preload scanner</strong> races ahead through the raw HTML, spotting images and stylesheets and fetching them early, so the network is never idle. The HTML parser performs <strong>speculative parsing</strong>, tentatively building structure it may have to revise. The browser defers work it can prove you won't see yet, decodes images off the main thread, and tears layout into incremental pieces. None of this changes the fundamental sequence — parse, style, layout, paint, composite — but it overlaps the waiting, so that by the time you could possibly notice, the work is already done. Fast feels fast not because the browser is doing less, but because it has become a master of doing things in the gaps.</p>`
